04382nam a22005055i 9780520971141DE-B159720191221113333.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191221s2018    cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209711417 a10.1525/97805209711412doi  a(DE-B1597)521181  a(OCoLC)1055047233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aKelly, William W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut.14aThe Sportsworld of the Hanshin Tigers :bProfessional Baseball in Modern Japan /cWilliam W. Kelly. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (321 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSport in World History ;v500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Terms and Japanese Language -- t1. Introducing Hanshin Tigers Baseball -- t2. The Rhythms of Tigers Baseball: Stadiums and Seasons -- t3. On the Field: Players, from Rookies to Veterans -- t4. In the Dugout: Manager and Coaches -- t5. In the Offices: Front Office and Parent Corporation -- t6. In the Stands: Fans, Followers, and Fair-Weather Spectators -- t7. In the Press Box: Sports Dailies and Mainstream Media -- t8. Baseball as Education and Entertainment -- t9. Workplace Melodramas and Second-City Complex -- t10. A Sportsworld Transforming: The Hanshin Tigers at Present -- tEndnotes -- tAppendix: A Note on the Research and Writing -- tGlossary of Key Japanese Terms -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBaseball has been Japan's most popular sport for over a century. The Sportsworld of the Hanshin Tigers analyzes Japanese baseball ethnographically by focusing on a single professional team, the Hanshin Tigers. For over fifty years, the Tigers have been the one of the country's most watched and talked-about professional baseball teams, second only to their powerful rivals, the Tokyo Yomiuri Giants. Despite a largely losing record, perennial frustration, and infighting among players, the Tigers remain overwhelming sentimental favorites in many parts of the country.   This book analyzes the Hanshin Tiger phenomenon, and offers an account of why it has long been so compelling and instructive. Author William Kelly argues that the Tigers represent what he calls a sportsworld -a collective product of the actions of players, coaching staff, management, media, and millions of passionate fans. The team has come to symbolize a powerful counter-narrative to idealized notions of Japanese workplace relations. The Tigers are savored as a melodramatic representation of real corporate life, rife with rivalries and office politics familiar to every Japanese worker. And playing in a historic stadium on the edge of Osaka, they carry the hopes and frustrations of Japan's second city against the all-powerful capital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520971141zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520971141.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles